{"id":69,"date":"2014-02-18T12:14:23","date_gmt":"2014-02-18T12:14:23","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/181.224.131.26\/~joannaba\/?page_id=69"},"modified":"2026-05-17T06:55:14","modified_gmt":"2026-05-17T05:55:14","slug":"about","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"http:\/\/jc-static-copy.local\/about\/","title":{"rendered":"About Me"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h1>\n\t\t\tAbout Joanna Courtney\t<\/h1>\n\t<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/jc-static-copy.local\/wp-content\/uploads\/kid-reading-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"kid reading\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" \/><\/p>\n<p>I wanted to be a writer from the moment I could read. As I child I was rarely to be seen without my head in a book and as a huge Enid Blyton enthusiast I soon began my own boarding-school novels about a girl called Daisy. Daisy sadly (or perhaps not-so sadly) got lost in the loft and never saw the light of day but my hunger was awakened.<\/p>\n<p>I kept an avid diary all the way up to University, although there I confess I discovered better things to do late at night! Continuing my passion for reading, I studied English literature and specialised in medieval literature. I still wanted to be a writer but the need to earn some money pushed me into a &#8216;proper job&#8217; as a factory planner. It wasn&#8217;t until I was married and living in Derbyshire, that I decided to try and make my passion pay. In the sparse hours available between raising two stepchildren and two more of my own, I wrote for the women&#8217;s magazines and began the long battle to get a novel published.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/jc-static-copy.local\/wp-content\/uploads\/champagne-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" \/>I signed to my fabulous agent, Kate Shaw, in 2007 for a contemporary novel but it wasn&#8217;t until I switched to writing historicals that we secured a publisher. It was one of the best moments of my life! PanMacmillan published my series, <em>The Queens of the Conquest<\/em>, and I then moved to the fabulous Piatkus to publish the <em>Shakespeare&#8217;s Queens<\/em> and <em>Queens of the East<\/em> series.<\/p>\n<p>Being a writer is a tough job but a hugely rewarding one. Stories are in my blood and, however painful it may be at times, I love the process of mining them out and onto paper and hope to be doing it for many, many years to come.<\/p>\n\t<p><strong>Introducing Anna Stuart&#8230;..<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>I also write World War II fiction as Anna Stuart. My aim in this period is still to explore the untold stories of female daring and heroism and the war was such an extraordinary time that there are plenty to be found. Women were liberated from the purely domestic arena and stepped up to take on all sorts of roles and jobs, both official and unofficial, and I hope readers enjoy their stories.<\/p>\n<p>To find out more about these novels, click across to my sister site on the button below.<\/p>\n<figure>\n\t\t\t\t<img decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/jc-static-copy.local\/wp-content\/uploads\/All-ww2-July-2025-5.jpg\" alt=\"Untitled design 1\" height=\"1080\" width=\"1557\" title=\"Untitled Design 1\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" loading=\"lazy\" \/>\n\t<\/figure>\n\t\t\t<a href=\"https:\/\/www.annastuartbooks.com\/\"  target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"    rel=\"noopener\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tAnna Stuart&#8217;s Site\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/a>\n\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>About Joanna Courtney I wanted to be a writer from the moment I could read. As I child I was rarely to be seen without my head in a book and as a huge Enid Blyton enthusiast I soon began my own boarding-school novels about a girl called Daisy. Daisy sadly (or perhaps not-so sadly)&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":5,"featured_media":74,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","template":"","meta":{"_acf_changed":false,"slim_seo":{"title":"About Me - Joanna Courtne